  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">G. R. Russell refers to the paper published by Dr. J. E. Snodgrass in Maryland. He mentions &quot;the notable stand&quot; of Cassius Marcellus Clay in Kentucky. Northern abolitionists are either excluded from the South or considered as extraneous and meddling. G. R. Russell believes that &quot;hard words do not make converts.&quot; He contrasts the abolitionists with the sympathetic, lukewarm class to which G. R. Russell belongs. He pays eloquent tribute to the devotion of the abolitionists.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">In the postscript, G. R. Russell writes that he has enclosed $25 to the support of the paper of Dr. Snodgrass.</subfield>
  </datafield>
